{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492883"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1177"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1177"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.15,0.07,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31507"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"658"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31507"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a three-day history of fever, sore throat, and pain on swallowing. She initially managed her symptoms with saltwater gargles, and yesterday felt some tender nodes in her neck. Her pain has worsened and this morning she could not open her mouth properly. She can now only speak with a husky voice. On examination, her mouth can be opened with difficulty. There is a foul foetor and the right anterior tonsillar pillar is swollen and the soft palate is bulging forward.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antiseptic gargles","Oral antibiotics","Parenteral antibiotics","Tonsillectomy","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has peri-tonsillar cellulitis complicated by a peritonsillar abscess (or quinsy). Peritonsillar abscess is a suppurative infection between the tonsils and the pharyngeal muscles. It is characterized by trismus, deviation of uvula, muffled or husky voice, and bulging of the soft palate. The finding of a unilateral swelling (above the tonsil) confirms the diagnosis of a peritonsillar abscess in this patient. The diagnosis is primarily clinical and should be managed with drainage and antibiotics. Different drainage techniques available are needle aspiration, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E, and tonsillectomy. Patients presenting with peritonsillar abscess for the first time are treated with needle aspiration or incision and drainage along with antibiotics. Tonsillectomy is reserved for patients who have failed incision and drainage or have recurrent episodes of peritonsillar abscess. Among the answer choices, the best management option for this patient is incision and drainage under general anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics and antiseptic gargles would be appropriate for tonsillitis due to a beta-haemolytic Streptococcus pyogenes infection. However, this patient has developed a complication of peri-tonsillar cellulitis and will need more than just antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary treatment of a peritonsillar abscess is drainage."],"references":["Galioto NJ. Peritonsillar Abscess Am Fam Physician 2017; 95:199-202."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1177"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-11T09:40:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T15:51:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1177"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31507"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Le